Species notes: reported as Boletus luteus L. and said to be common.
Site notes: data from a list of fungi prepared by Paterson for inclusion in "Lists of the Fauna and Flora of the West of Scotland" which was published to mark the visit to Glasgow of the British Association for the Advancement of Science in September 1876. Date range derived from the time of Paterson's application for membership of the GFNS in early July 1875 (when aged 20; admitted on 20th July) to the time of publication, although it is possible some records might pre-date this period by a year or two. Grid reference approximate: taxa which have not been assigned to a specific location but listed simply as "common" have been placed in Cadder Wilderness, the station most exhaustively researched by Paterson, where he "gathered between seven and eight hundred species". Caution: there will be some cases where this assumption is erroneous.
Source: Lists of the Fauna and Flora of the West of Scotland (1876); p.118

Site notes: data from a list of fungi prepared by Paterson for inclusion in "Lists of the Fauna and Flora of the West of Scotland" which was published to mark the visit to Glasgow of the British Association for the Advancement of Science in September 1876. Date range derived from the time of Paterson's application for membership of the GFNS in early July 1875 (when aged 20; admitted on 20th July) to the time of publication, although it is possible some records might pre-date this period by a year or two. Grid reference approximate: taxa which have not been assigned to a specific location but listed simply as "common" have been placed in Cadder Wilderness, the station most exhaustively researched by Paterson, where he "gathered between seven and eight hundred species". Caution: there will be some cases where this assumption is erroneous.
Source: Lists of the Fauna and Flora of the West of Scotland (1876); p.118
